Hi Viktor , nice to meet you ! Sorry for taking for ever to come back to you , but I’m in the middle of crunch time for a project that will be released in June .
Send me your work at anytime ,
I will have a look .
Let me know where you stand with your thesis ,
What is your visual and narrative goal ,
What are your references , basically understand where you started and where you want to push your project .
I haven’t been on Annecy but at Dneg we have been recruiting there 
Excited to see your work ,and feel free to ask me any question about the industry 
Cheers 
Johnny

Hi, yeah that's fine, hope its not too stressful! So For my look development project, I'm creating scenes based within the New Orleans, in the 1900s. I'm creating the environments in a realistic style. I've currently in the texturing stage of my project. I have 5 shots of my environment which I would like your opinion on. I'm creating the scenes in Maya and using Zbrush and photoshop to texture. The background in my wide shot will have a matt painting. The tree models are not final. I won't include any leaves as it will obstruct the view of some of my models. I have chosen a jazz player to be in my scene but finding it hard to add narrative to my shots due to only having one character and no time to animate him. I have hierarchy in my scene in the way I chose to model my assets. I spent more time on assets that are closer to my camera. I'm using bump maps and normal maps to add details to my objects. Each scene will be lit to portray different times of the day and I will include rain in one of my scenes. I'm using three-point lighting and will have light coming from other parts like the lampposts. This is what I have so far and will be happy to receive your feedback on it. Below are the shots of my scenes and the character I modelled.
